english:
  title: Epitaph and Preface for Master Mokun, Lord Yi Munjung, Particularly Commended Official of Chosŏn
  author: Ha Ryun
  language: eng
  text: |-
    Among those who ascended to the civil service through learning and first illuminated the East with Neo-Confucian principles, reaching the highest office of Prime Minister, there was only Master Mokun of Han Mountain, the venerable Yi Munjung. In the autumn of 1365, when this gentleman and Master Sŏngsan the Recluse Yi Mun-ch'ung jointly presided over the examination halls, I, Ha Ryun, though lacking in talent, was fortunate enough to pass the examination and served as your disciple for more than thirty years. Though you have passed away, duty prevented me from going to weep at your grave, and my sorrow remains unhealed to this day. Now your youngest son, Song-sŏn, has brought the account of your life written by Yang-ch'on Kwŏn Kŭn, requesting that I compose this epitaph. I greatly fear my words cannot adequately capture your virtue and excellence, yet conscience forbids me to decline.

    According to the record: Your name was Saek, your courtesy name was Yŏng-suk, and your pen name was Mokun. Your family had dwelt for generations in Han Prefecture of Ch'ungch'ŏng Province. Your great-grandfather, whose name was Ch'ang-se, received posthumous rank as Minister of Personnel. Your grandfather, Cha-sŏng, was posthumously granted the title of Vice Director of the Secretariat by the Yuan court, and received the rank of Minister of the Right Deliberative Council in our nation. Your father, whose name was Kok, served as Vice Director of the Bureau of Personnel under the Yuan's Eastern Conquest Provincial Secretariat, and in our nation held the posts of Minister of the Right Deliberative Council, Chief Minister of the Bureau of Rites and Culture, and Superintendent of the Spring and Autumn Institute. His pen name was Kajeong and his posthumous name was Lord of Filial Culture. He passed the imperial examination during the Yuan's Tongbuk period and was renowned for his poetry and prose, with a collected works still transmitted in the world.

    Your mother was Lady Kim, granted the title of County Duchess of Liaoyang by the Yuan and Duchess of Hamch'ang by our nation. She bore you on the fifth month, day jiwei of the Tianli year 1328. From childhood you were extraordinarily brilliant—upon reading something once, you could recite it perfectly. In 1361 you passed the examination of the National Academy at age fourteen. In 1368, when your father served as Registrar of the Central Secretariat in the Yuan court, you were enrolled as a student of the National University and made remarkable progress in your studies. In 1370 your father returned to our nation, and the following January he passed away. You fulfilled your filial duties through the period of mourning. In the summer of 1373 you ranked first in the examination of the Bureau of Rites. That autumn you placed first in the provincial examination of the Eastern Conquest Provincial Secretariat. In spring 1374 you went to the capital for the imperial examination, where your response to the palace examination so impressed the chief examiners that you placed second in the second tier of successful candidates. You were appointed Probationary Hanlin Academician and Concurrently Draftsman of Edicts and Editor of the National History Institute. Upon returning to our nation, the king honored you with special courtesy and appointed you Concurrently Minister of Rites, Instructor of the Bureau of Rites and Culture, and Editor of the Spring and Autumn Institute.

    In spring 1375 you became Darughachi of the Royal Household, and were promoted to Inner Secretariat Attendant and Draftsman, Concurrently holding your other positions. That summer you went to the capital to serve the examination system, and in winter served as Acting Director. Seeing that the realm was descending into chaos, you cited your mother's advanced age and resigned to return home. In autumn 1376, when our nation reformed its official system, you were appointed Vice Minister of Personnel and Concurrently Vice Minister of War, participating in the selection of both civil and military officials. You had previously submitted eight proposals for governmental reform, one of which called for abolishing the private secretariat and restoring the personnel selection process to the proper ministries—hence this appointment.

    In 1377 you became National University Director and Keeper of the Palace Gates, then Vice Remonstrance Official. In 1378, when your colleagues all suffered demotion for their remonstrances to the throne, the king said to his ministers: "Yi Saek is incomparable to ordinary men." He then elevated you to Vice Commissioner of the Secret Secretariat, from which you rose through several promotions to Left Commissioner. From that point you participated in state secrets for seven years, your counsel proving invaluable. In the winter of 1381, when the Red Bandits captured the capital, you followed the king in defense and played a key role in its recovery. You received first-rank merit and were granted an iron deed of merit.

    In 1383 the Yuan appointed you Superintendent of Confucian Learning of the Eastern Conquest Provincial Secretariat, while our nation appointed you Secret Advisor and Concurrently Director of the Spring and Autumn Institute, granting you the title Loyal and Righteous Meritorious Subject. Thereafter you participated in the governance of the realm. In 1375 as Concurrently Chief Examiner you requested implementation of methods to investigate and restrict unauthorized books. In 1377 the Yuan appointed you Vice Director of the Bureau of Personnel of the Eastern Conquest Provincial Secretariat. In 1378 you became Prefect of Kaesŏng and Concurrently Grand Director of the National Academy. When the king wished to revive schools, he reorganized the National Academy, appointing accomplished scholars in classical learning to teach, all holding concurrent posts. Daily you and your fellow educators would divide the teaching duties, then gather to discuss and debate points of doctrine, continuing until sunset without fatigue. Through your efforts, students abandoned old habits and the scholarly atmosphere was thoroughly renewed.

    That summer the king tested the nine halls on interpretation of the Six Classics and selected seven successful graduates. He had you read and judge their papers. In 1379 you again served as Chief Examiner, implementing the system of comprehensive examination in three sessions. Earlier, when the king wished to construct a memorial hall for Princess Noguk at the eastern slope of Wangyun Temple, but found the location too confined, he examined a new site to the west of Ma Rock that was far grander. The Attendant Liu Zhuo and others submitted a memorial requesting that the work be halted. The king was enraged, imprisoned Liu Zhuo and others, intending to execute them, and ordered you to compose an edict to the people. You asked what charges they faced. The king enumerated four charges against them. You replied: "These are all matters of the past, and by law they do not warrant death. Recently Liu the Attendant and others submitted a memorial requesting suspension of the memorial hall work. Even if punished for this, all the realm would say it was because they submitted this memorial. May the king reflect upon this." The king grew more enraged and pressed you to complete the edict. You prostrated yourself and said: "How could this humble minister dare compose a text to compound their crimes?" The king's anger intensified. He moved you to the Consort's quarters and cut off your food.

    The next day, the favored minister Shin Tŏn, seeking to assuage the king's wrath, requested that you be imprisoned for disobeying the royal command. You said: "This humble minister, unworthy though I am, rose from humble birth to high office through the king's favor. Long I have believed that when I can serve to perfect the sovereign's virtue, I must speak plainly without concealment. Now if the king seeks to execute Minister Liu, I dared speak earnestly only from fear that the king's name would be tarnished in the eyes of the world and posterity." When the prison official reported your words to the king, he was moved to sudden understanding. He released Liu Zhuo and the others, and sent word: "Tomorrow, after bathing, come to court. I shall apologize to you." Thereafter the king held you in even greater respect and deference.

    In 1381 you became Chief Examiner, and that autumn rose to Minister of the State Council. The king granted you the additional title Loyal and Righteous Protector of Righteous Conduct and Admirer of Transformation. Whenever the king summoned you, he would sweep the room and burn incense, saying: "The learning of Yi Saek is rarely matched even in the Middle Kingdom. How could I not show respect?" In the ninth month you suffered the loss of your mother, the County Duchess. The following June the king ordered your restoration to office, but you earnestly declined. In the winter of 1383 you were enfeoffed as Lord of Han Mountain. In autumn 1384 the king passed away. Since your mother's death, you had been troubled by illness; upon hearing of the king's passing, you closed your doors and emerged not for seven years.

    In 1387 you were granted the title Promoter of Loyalty, Protector of Righteous Conduct, Concordant Virtue, and Admirer of Transformation, becoming Director of the Bureau of Rites and Culture and the Spring and Autumn Institute. In 1392 you became Judge of the Three Departments. In 1393 you were reconfirmed as Lord of Han Mountain. In 1394 you received additional rank. In 1395 you were transferred to Inspector of the Gate Below Heaven. In 1396 you again served as Chief Examiner—in total you presided over examinations five times, selecting many distinguished scholars. In 1398, when the Ming court wished to establish the Tielingwei garrison, the military commander Ch'oe Yŏng, allied with pretenders, launched an invasion toward Liaodong. When our Dowager Sovereign raised a righteous force to turn back the army and captured Ch'oe Yŏng and his followers, the court appointed you Gate Below Heaven Official. You said: "Now the realm faces crisis, the king is young and cannot attend court personally, and those in charge must act accordingly. How would an aged minister dare volunteer?" Both the king and the realm urged you to decline, citing your advanced age and infirmity. You replied: "I have received boundless kindness from the nation and have always hoped to repay it with my life. If I can convey the realm's commands to the Son of Heaven, though I die, it is as living." You proceeded to the Ming court, where you presented your case with precision and eloquence. The Hongwu Emperor treated you with exceptional honor and loaded you with gifts before your return.

    In summer 1399 you returned home. That autumn you requested retirement from arduous duties due to illness, becoming Judge of the Gate Below Heaven Bureau. In winter when the Respectful and Yielding Lord ascended the throne, those who resented your refusal to support them impeached you, resulting in your banishment to Changtan County. In April 1400 you were moved to Hamch'ang. In May the case involving Yun I and Yi Ch'o erupted. Several dozen people, including yourself, were imprisoned in Ch'ŏngju, where officials prepared severe torture to extract false confessions. The situation seemed dire, yet you maintained your integrity and righteousness, unmoved. Suddenly great rains fell from morning through midday. Mountains collapsed, waters surged, city walls crumbled, and official buildings were submerged. The interrogating officials barely escaped by clinging to trees. News was rushed to the court, which issued orders to release all the prisoners. The elders of Ch'ŏngju said to one another: "Since this district was established, we have never seen such severe flooding. This surely reflects the resentment of these men."

    The king had long known your integrity and made repeated attempts to recall you, but those who resented you constantly obstructed his efforts. In the winter of 1401 you were summoned from Hamch'ang and reconfirmed as Lord of Han Mountain with Palace Rank. In April 1402 you were again exiled to Kŭmju, then in June transferred to Yŏhŭng. In July when our Dowager Sovereign ascended the throne, those who resented you brought false accusations and sought your execution. You said: "Throughout my life I have not spoken falsely. How could I falsely confess to calumnies? Even dead, I shall be an upright spirit, with nothing to regret." Your words reached the throne, and the king pardoned you, transferring you to Changhŭng Prefecture. Many others exiled at the same time benefited from your steadfast integrity and were spared. That winter you were released and returned to Han Prefecture.

    In autumn 1403 you traveled to Kangdong and entered Five-Peak Mountain, where you remained. The king sent envoys to escort you back, enfeoffing you as Lord of Han Mountain and treating you with the courtesy of an old friend. Whenever you had audience and withdrew, the king himself would accompany you to the middle gate. In summer 1404, the fifth month, you requested leave to escape the heat at Yŏ River. On the seventh day of the fifth month your illness became critical. A Buddhist monk came and wished to discuss his teachings with you. You waved him away, saying: "The principle of life and death is clear to me—I harbor no doubt." With these words you passed away at the age of sixty-nine.

    When news of your death reached the court, the king reduced his meals and suspended audiences for three days. He sent envoys to make offerings and provided for your funeral with full ceremony, bestowing upon you the posthumous name Lord Munjung. In the tenth month your son Song-sŏn and others escorted your coffin back to Han Prefecture. On the eleventh month, jiayinday, you were buried at Kaji Plain.

    Your nature was pure and crystalline, your learning precise and penetrating. Early you received your family's teachings and entered the National Academy, where you studied broadly and cultivated yourself diligently in Neo-Confucian philosophy. After returning to our nation, you devoted yourself to nurturing the rising generation and took as your responsibility the restoration of the Way—scholars revered you as they might the polar star. For more than thirty years you wielded the nation's brush in composing state documents, earning consistent praise from the court. When you took up your brush to compose poetry and prose, the words flowed without pause; your style was refined and your meanings penetrating, extraordinary for your age. Your collected works comprise fifty-five volumes. Your friend the Recluse of Star Mountain, learned and discerning, rarely praised others, yet he spoke of you without end, saying: "Mokun is truly a heaven-born talent." In daily intercourse, you met people and handled affairs with perfect equanimity, a gentle harmony surrounding you. In your official conduct, your counsel was incisive and firm, unmoved by opposition. As Prime Minister, you upheld great principles and never sought personal advancement. Throughout your life you accumulated no property; though you were sometimes in want, this never troubled you. In your later years, living at leisure, you often wandered mountains and waters for diversion. You did not reject monks and Taoists who wished to follow you, and you never grudged your poetry and prose to those who requested them. Some criticized you for not firmly rejecting heterodox teachings. Yet with your penetrating understanding of principle, how could you truly have believed in illusory doctrines? One may know this from the simple words you spoke at your passing.

    Your wife, Lady Kwŏn of Yongga, daughter of the Yuan's Brigadier General and our nation's Lord of Flower Garden Kwŏn Chung-dal, and granddaughter of the Yuan's Left Counselor of the Crown Prince and our nation's Right Minister of the Deliberative Council Kwŏn Han-gong, possessed worthy virtue and exemplary conduct, maintaining wifely propriety and never disturbing your peace through concerns about wealth or want. She bore three sons: Song-dŏk, who became a Loyal and Trustworthy Merit Subject and Concurrent Secret Adviser; Song-hak, who became Concurrent Secretary of the Secret Secretariat and passed the examination in 1376, serving as Concurrent Chief Examiner in 1399, both dying before you; and Song-sŏn, who became Censor and passed the examination in 1392. You had four grandsons through the line of the Secret Adviser: Maeng-yu, who became Director of the Military Equipment Bureau; Maeng-gyun, who became Concurrent Director of Culture and Arts and passed the examination of 1395; Maeng-jun, who passed the examination of 1402; and Maeng-jin, who became Keeper of the Stables. Two granddaughters married Lord of Serene Repose Liu I and Concurrent Chief Commander Ha Ku. Through the Secretary line there are six great-grandsons and a great-granddaughter who married Upright Official Yi Chŏm. Through the Censor line there are three great-great-grandsons, the eldest named Ki-ch'o.

    The Epitaph reads:

    From Han came forth one bright with talent,
    Who bore up Kajeong's legacy.
    With brilliance as gems wrought in prose,
    He gained the prize at the imperial court.

    Ah, resplendent Lord Munjung!
    Truly you transmitted the Classics.
    Early entering the great academy,
    You spread your fragrant influence wide.
    Graded in the second rank supreme,
    You rose through halls of jade.
    Your voice grew ever louder,
    Bringing luster to kingdom and state.

    Returning to the eastern realm,
    You became a teacher to all.
    Your principles penetrating and subtle,
    You inherited Cheng and Zhu.
    Your style lofty and ancient,
    You surpassed Su and Huang.
    The Way accumulated in your person,
    Your conduct serene and measured.
    Your virtue grew with your years,
    Your rank supreme in the court.

    Bearing the royal commission,
    You won respect from Heaven's throne.
    Returning, you sought retirement,
    Your advance and retreat both perfect.
    When times grew dark and troubled,
    Heaven's will lay distant and dim.
    In that season of perilous trials,
    The people mourned with breaking hearts.
    When Taishan fell in collapse,
    Travelers on the road wept bitter tears.

    Alas, venerable master!
    Your virtue's voice shall not fade.
    May your descendants inherit your ways,
    That blessing and fortune endure without end.
    I offer this epitaph without flattery,
    That it illumine the ages to come.
  footnotes:
    - Mokun (牧隱) and Chŏngsŏk (文靖 - posthumous name) refer to Yi Saek (李穡), one of Korea's most eminent Neo-Confucian scholars of the 14th century.
    - The Red Bandit incident (紅寇) refers to uprisings by the Red Turbans, a millenarian movement that threatened both the Yuan and early Chosŏn.
    - The examination system referenced includes the provincial (鄕試), capital (會試), and palace (殿試) examinations modeled on the Chinese imperial system.
    - The reference to 'Cheng and Zhu' (程張) alludes to the Neo-Confucian philosophers Cheng Yi and Chu Xi, representing the philosophical lineage Ha Ryun wished to honor.
    - Ha Ryun's composition appears designed as both epitaph and autobiography, reflecting his intimate knowledge of Yi Saek's career and their shared scholarly commitments.
